When creating a CompoundDirectedGraph with Subgraphs, if the direction is EAST (not the default), the graph changes direction, but the Subgraphs do not.
I am using the current HEAD from dev.eclipse.org CVS.

This is easy to test by adding the following to any of the CompoundDirectedGraph examples (say CompoundGraphTests.aaaapull()):
graph.setDirection(PositionConstants.EAST);

e.g.:
CompoundDirectedGraph graph = new CompoundDirectedGraph();
graph.nodes = nodes;
graph.edges = edges;
graph.setDirection(PositionConstants.EAST);
new CompoundDirectedGraphLayout().visit(graph);

* I put this in SWT, as I couldn't find the Draw2D Component/category.

If an editModel ID is used, then ArtifactEdit.getAdapter should be overwritten by classes that extend it.  This way the correct ArtifactEditModel is returned every time.  If the method is not overwritten, calling ArtifactEdit.getAdapter results in a call to ArtifactEditAdapterFactory.getAdapter, which does a search based on whether the project contains one of the registered editModelIDs.  The problem occurs when a project has multiple editModel IDs. The call to ArtifactEditAdapterFactory.getAdapter will result in returning the first ArtifactEditModel it finds a matching editModelID for - not the correct one.  Specifically, the problem occurs with the WebArtifactEdit.  

For example, we have a project that has both a Web Module and Foo Module, with its own editModel ID. So both jst.web and foo.id are registered editModelIDs.  In this case, the EditModelRegistry has the foo.id before jst.web.  If we open FooEditor and do not overwrite the ArtifactEdit.getAdapter method, it will use the ArtifactEditAdapterFactory.getAdapter and find the correct JavaArtifactEditModel for FooArtifactEdit.  If we then open web.xml, it will make the same call and return the same JavaArtifactEditModel, because it matched the foo.id before it got to jst.web id.  This will result in not being able to save changes to web.xml because it is using the wrong JavaArtifactEditModel to determine whether save is necessary.

The solution is for both WebArtifactEdit and FooArtifactEdit to overwrite getAdapter and always return the JavaArtifactEditModel that matches its editModelID.  It should also be documented as a general rule that all ArtifactEdits that register an EditModel ID should overwrite the getAdapter method.

Below is a suggestion of what the getAdapter method that should be added to WebArtifactEdit should look like:

	public Object getAdapter(Class adapterType) {
		IProject aProject = this.getProject();
		URI componentURI = ModuleURIUtil.fullyQualifyURI(aProject);
		ModuleCoreNature nature = ModuleCoreNature.getModuleCoreNature(this.getComponent().getProject());
		Map params = new HashMap();
		params.put(ArtifactEditModelFactory.PARAM_MODULE_URI, componentURI);
		EditModel editModel = nature.getExistingEditModel("jst.web",params,this.isReadOnly());
		return editModel;
	}

I think we can just replace the implementation on ArtifactEdit to be the following:

public Object getAdapter(Class adapterType) {
		if (adapterType == ArtifactEditModel.class)
			return getArtifactEditModel();
		return Platform.getAdapterManager().getAdapter(this, adapterType);
	}

There is no need for us to do the overhead of following the adapter pattern when we know we have the right edit model cached in the artifact edit instance.

